I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation to be able to form connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during an age of gold for media, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We plunged directly into the things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without having any reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become foundations for our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
It resembled nothing of what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are suddenly available and everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specific enclosed spaces.
Subconsciously, I die of desire to connect with the universal community that surrounded all of this.
That's why so many of us watch shows like The Office or films like Anchorman, with lots of short references, just like memes, with such obsession.
We repeated these refs to each other, knowing that most people already knew them.
Now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
There are too many things to see and no way to rationalize them all... will we escape hyper-saturation?
We get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize eventually that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We are forced to deal with a situation where we hold onto nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art to which we connect can be very imperfect.
One enters into parasocial relationships by paying more attention.
One understands that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
Without collective consciousness regarding the media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
Some of us continue to place people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a turbulent period and I can't wait to see where it's going to lead us.
